# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ot-security-ics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In the U.S., **critical infrastructure protection** (**CIP**) is a concept that relates to the preparedness and response to serious incidents that involve the critical infrastructure of a region or the nation.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The American Presidential directive PDD-63 of May 1998 set up a national program of "Critical Infrastructure Protection".
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In 2014 the NIST Cybersecurity Framework was published after further presidential directives.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] CIP is a national program to ensure the security of vulnerable and interconnected infrastructures of the United States.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In May 1998, President Bill Clinton issued presidential directive PDD-63 on the subject of critical infrastructure protection.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This recognized certain parts of the national infrastructure as critical to the national and economic security of the United States and the well-being of its citizenry, and required steps to be taken to protect it.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This was updated on December 17, 2003, by President George W.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Bush through Homeland Security Presidential Directive HSPD-7 for **Critical Infrastructure Identification, Prioritization, and Protection**.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The updated directive would add in agriculture to the list of critical infrastructure within the country; this would undo the omission of agriculture from the 1998 presidential directive.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Take, for example, a computer virus that disrupts the distribution of natural gas across a region.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This could lead to a consequential reduction in electrical power generation, which in turn leads to the forced shutdown of computerized controls and communications.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Road traffic, air traffic, and rail transportation might then become affected.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Emergency services might also be hampered.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] An entire region can become debilitated because some critical elements in the infrastructure become disabled through natural disaster.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] While potentially in contravention of the Geneva Conventions, military forces have also recognized that it can cripple an enemy's ability to resist by attacking key elements of its civilian and military infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The federal government has developed a standardized description of critical infrastructure, in order to facilitate monitoring and preparation for disabling events.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] With much of the critical infrastructure privately owned, the Department of Defense (DoD) depends on commercial infrastructure to support its normal operations.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The Department of State and the Central Intelligence Agency are also involved in intelligence analysis with friendly countries.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] On March 9, 1999, Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre warned the United States Congress of a cyber terrorist "electronic Pearl Harbor" saying, "It is not going to be against Navy ships sitting in a Navy shipyard.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] It is going to be against commercial infrastructure".
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Later this fear was qualified by President Clinton after reports of actual cyber terrorist attacks in 2000: "I think it was an alarm.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] We lost our Pacific fleet at Pearl Harbor.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There are many examples of computer systems that have been hacked or victims of extortion.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] One such example occurred in September 1995 where a Russian national allegedly masterminded the break-in of Citicorp's electronic funds transfer system and was ordered to stand trial in the United States.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] A gang of hackers under his leadership had breached Citicorp's security 40 times during 1994.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] They were able to transfer $12 million from customer accounts and withdraw an estimated $400,000.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In the past, the systems and networks of the infrastructure elements were physically and logically independent and separate.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] They had little interaction or connection with each other or other sectors of the infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] With advances in technology, the systems within each sector became automated, and interlinked through computers and communications facilities.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] As a result, the flow of electricity, oil, gas, and telecommunications throughout the country are linked—albeit sometimes indirectly—but the resulting linkages blur traditional security borders.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] While this increased reliance on interlinked capabilities helps make the economy and nation more efficient and perhaps stronger, it also makes the country more vulnerable to disruption and attack.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This interdependent and interrelated infrastructure is more vulnerable to physical and cyber disruptions because it has become a complex system with single points of failure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In the past an incident that would have been an isolated failure can now cause widespread disruption because of cascading effects.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] As an example, capabilities within the information and communication sector have enabled the United States to reshape its government and business processes, while becoming increasingly software driven.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] One catastrophic failure in this sector now has the potential to bring down multiple systems including air traffic control, emergency services, banking, trains, electrical power, and dam control.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The elements of the infrastructure themselves are also considered possible targets of terrorism.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] For example, the 2022 attack on North Carolina’s power substations near Carthage leaving tens of thousands of residents without power.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The ordeal left residents without proper heating, hot water, and the ability to cook for days as repairs took place.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Authorities noted that the attack was intentionally committed via gunfire.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Traditionally, critical infrastructure elements have been lucrative targets for anyone wanting to attack another country.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Now, because the infrastructure has become a national lifeline, terrorists can achieve high economic and political value by attacking elements of it.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Disrupting or even disabling the infrastructure may reduce the ability to defend the nation, erode public confidence in critical services, and reduce economic strength.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Additionally, well chosen terrorist attacks can become easier and less costly than traditional warfare because of the interdependence of infrastructure elements.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These infrastructure elements can become easier targets where there is a low probability of detection.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The elements of the infrastructure are also increasingly vulnerable to a dangerous mix of traditional and nontraditional types of threats.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Traditional and non-traditional threats include equipment failures, human error, weather and natural causes, physical attacks, and cyber-attacks.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] For each of these threats, the cascading effect caused by single points of failure has the potential to pose dire and far-reaching consequences.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There are fears from global leaders that the frequency and severity of critical infrastructure incidents will increase in the future.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These infrastructure failures are prone to greatly affect the country’s residents who are on high alert.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] One of these future potential failures can be seen within the cyber security world as American citizens fear that their technological infrastructure is at risk.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This comes as the world becomes more technologically advanced with the introduction of AI and technology into many areas of American life.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Although efforts are under way, there is no unified national capability to protect the interrelated aspects of the country's infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] One reason for this is that a good understanding of the inter-relationships does not exist.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There is also no consensus on how the elements of the infrastructure mesh together, or how each element functions and affects the others.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Securing national infrastructure depends on understanding the relationships among its elements as well as the immediate and delayed effects that these failures may have on residents.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Thus, when one sector scheduled a three-week drill to mimic the effects of a pandemic flu, even though two-thirds of the participants claimed to have business continuity plans in place, barely half reported that their plan was moderately effective.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These can have drastic effects on those who do not have access to the necessary safeguards in place to protect themselves.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Some of the most critical infrastructure for any in the US are the roads, hospitals, and infrastructure that provides food to residents.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] An increased risk of the collapse of these critical infrastructure points can lead to, and in most cases have led to, drastic decreases in access to water, food, medical attention, and electricity.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Critical needs for residents trapped in their homes and areas, residents who rely on medication or need to be transported to the nearest hospital, and residents who are heavily affected by malnutrition.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This was seen during the 2005 Hurricane Katrina aftermath in new Orleans as thousands were displaced, hundreds killed, and thousands more injured with no clear way of receiving shelter or assistance.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There is a current movement to improve critical infrastructure with residents in mind.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Critical infrastructure protection requires the development of a national capability to identify and monitor the critical elements and to determine when and if the elements are under attack or are the victim of destructive natural occurrences.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These natural occurrences have become more of a threat over the past couple of years due to climate change; increased occurrences of stronger storms, longer droughts, and rising sea levels.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] CIP's is importance is the link between risk management and infrastructure assurance.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] It provides the capability needed to eliminate potential vulnerabilities in the critical infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] CIP practitioners determine vulnerabilities and analyze alternatives to prepare for incidents.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] They focus on improving the capability to detect and warn of impending attacks on, and system failures within, the critical elements of the national infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] However, there are skeptics that see certain national infrastructure methods as harm to the communities that local and federal governments swore to protect.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This is a key factor in the movement against Atlanta’s “Cop City” as residents say that there are negative systematic affects as well as negative environmental affects as well.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The Atlanta Public Safety Training Center, also known as, “Cop City” is one of the many examples of critical infrastructure created to try and serve the purpose of protecting the civilian populations.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This form of critical infrastructure is one that works indirectly as the project aims to train current and incoming police officers and combat units.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The plan is one that was put forth by the Atlanta Police Foundation in 2017 called the “Vision Safe Atlanta – Public Safety Action Plan.” This plan sees the police foundation receiving upgrades and attention to the crumbling infrastructure of police buildings and necessities throughout Atlanta.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The largest addition to the foundation and police force’s portfolio is about 85 acres of the city’s greenspace to construct a state-of-the-art training facility.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The Atlanta Police Foundation is a private entity that works for the betterment of the city’s police force.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] According to the Atlanta Police Foundation, a private entity, the project has the backing of CEOs in the area along with public officials who not only have support for the foundation but support for the $90 million project which would lease and raze about 85 acres of publicly owned forests.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] According to… the center is being privately funded by other private entities with 2/3 of funding coming from private finance and the other third coming from taxpayer dollars.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These facilities include “a firing range, a burn building, and a ‘kill house’ designed to mimic urban combat scenarios”.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The overall goal of the facility is to ensure that Atlanta police officers are getting better training within the city whiles also getting a fresh space.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Although a positive outlook for the Police Foundation and the Atlanta Police Department, the facility has faced some pushback from the public in terms of the destruction of public land as well as police misconduct concerns.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Atlanta is a city that is surrounded by large and lush green foliage earning the title of a “a city in a forest” by residents and visitors; according to residents, the importance of the city’s forests cannot be understated.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] With such a large presence of trees and green space, residents see these spaces as a vital part of the city’s natural ecosystems.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Residents are concerned that the clearing of 85 acres of the forest will bring about an increase in poor air quality, decrease natural habitats in the area, and increase flooding in a vulnerable community which happens to be predominantly black.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Residents believe that the potential ecological damage was too much of a risk for some residents to stay idle; this is in addition to the potential increase of police violence.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The movement to stop “cop city” came about as the calls to defund the Atlanta Police Department grew in the wake of calls to defund police departments across the country.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There have been numerous organizations working to prevent construction from beginning through acts of moving into the forest, sabotaging equipment, and seeking legal action against the city and private companies who are working to supply equipment for the construction of the facility.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Many people outside of the community worked to stop “cop city” as well.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The forest that the Police Foundation seeks to build their facility on is a part of Native Muscogee land.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Tribe members traveled to the city to demand that the city end work and retreat from Muscogee land.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The movement to stop “cop city” became a group effort by individuals who wanted to see change in the justice system in Atlanta as well as individuals who wanted to protect the natural habitats as they seek justice for the nonhuman species of Atlanta’s forests.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Although a growing movement, there is pushback from the city and the Police Foundation who want the so called “cop city” to go forward and will do anything to get it done.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In defending the forest and trying to be heard and recognized by the city and the state government, protestors were met with harsh punishments; both legal and physical.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In protesting, a nonbinary environmental activist named Manuel Esteban Paez Terán, or Tortuguita, was killed by Georgia State Patrol on January 18 bringing to light the violent effects of police patrol and watch over protestors.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] As much as protestors are speaking up and out about the environmental destruction and negative effects of infrastructure, there are many laws and policies going into place that make it harder to exercise one’s free speech.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Critical Infrastructure (CI) Trespass Bills are being introduced across the country to allow for the detention and prosecution of protestors that get in the way of infrastructure construction.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] According to Jalbert et. al. and if these bills become law, they will allow for the use of drones, excessive force, facial recognition, and community surveillance tactics.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Further, Akbar, Love, and Donoghoe argue that these bills will disproportionality affect protestors of color.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This is seen by the death of Tortuguita and the mass arrest of Indigenous, black, and brown protesters.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Not only are there arrests and violent responses by law authorities, but there are also actions that officials are taking to make CI trespassing a felony as many cite the protest of critical infrastructure to be terroristic actions.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These laws stem from the growing systematic push to criminalize protestors from preventing the construction of new critical infrastructure; these laws are in response to country wide protests against pipeline construction.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These are protests that stem from the desire to protect the climate and to protect Indigenous lands.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Protests tend to work to stop/slow the construction of new pipelines and aim to speak out against the local, state, and federal governments who support, and in many cases, fund the addition of oil and gas pipelines.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Indigenous peoples argue that pipeline construction goes against tribal treaties as well as has the possibility to jeopardize the land through pollution.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The intertwining of alleged environmental and systemic oppression has pushed residents of areas due for pipeline construction to speak out and against the projects.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Due to oil and gas pipelines falling under the sector of energy, they are seen as critical infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Therefore, the US government aims to uphold and protect them.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] As a result, multiple states have deployed “Anti-Protest” laws to prevent the disruption of pipeline construction and any development of projects considered to be critical infrastructure and necessary for the advancement of the country.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These laws make it a felony to stall and prevent the construction and development of critical infrastructure projects within states that implement these various “anti-protest” laws.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Due to the growing political push to prevent protesters from interfering in infrastructure projects, Georgia has become a state that is slowly using “anti-protest” laws and measures to prevent people from protesting “cop city” and other critical infrastructure projects in the state.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Activists have been detained and charged with felonies as they protest “cop city”.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Critical Infrastructure Projects in the US has its supporters and its protestors and the response to these projects are made clear from all sides.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] PDD-63 mandated the formation of a national structure for critical infrastructure protection.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] To accomplish this one of the primary actions was to produce a National Infrastructure Assurance Plan, or NIAP, later renamed National Infrastructure Protection Plan or NIPP.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The different entities of the national CIP structure work together as a partnership between the government and the public sectors.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Each department and agency of the federal government is responsible for protecting its portion of the government's critical infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In addition, there are grants made available through the Department of Homeland Security for municipal and private entities to use for CIP and security purposes.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These include grants for emergency management, water security training, rail, transit and port security, metropolitan medical response, LEA terrorism prevention programs and the Urban Areas Security Initiative.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] PDD-63 identified certain functions related to critical infrastructure protection that must be performed chiefly by the federal government.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These are national defense, foreign affairs, intelligence, and law enforcement.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Each lead agency for these special functions appoints a senior official to serve as a functional coordinator for the federal government.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In 2008 a mobile PDA-based Vulnerability Assessment Security Survey Tool (VASST) was introduced to speed physical security assessment of critical infrastructure by law enforcement to meet compliance requirements of PDD-63.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The **National Infrastructure Protection Plan** (NIPP) is a document called for by Homeland Security Presidential Directive 7, which aims to unify Critical Infrastructure and Key Resource (CIKR) protection efforts across the country.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The latest version of the plan was produced in 2013 The NIPP's goals are to protect critical infrastructure and key resources and ensure resiliency.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] It is generally considered unwieldy and not an actual plan to be carried out in an emergency, but it is useful as a mechanism for developing coordination between government and the private sector.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The NIPP is based on the model laid out in the 1998 Presidential Decision Directive-63, which identified critical sectors of the economy and tasked relevant government agencies to work with them on sharing information and on strengthening responses to attack.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The NIPP is structured to create partnerships between Government Coordinating Councils (GCC) from the public sector and Sector Coordinating Councils (SCC) from the private sector for the eighteen sectors DHS has identified as critical.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] For each of the identified major sectors of the critical infrastructure, the federal government appointed a Sector Liaison Official from a designated Lead Agency.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] A private sector counterpart, a Sector Coordinator, was also identified.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Together, the two sector representatives, one federal government and one corporate, were responsible for developing a sector NIAP.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In addition, each department and agency of the federal government was responsible for developing its own CIP plan for protecting its portion of the federal government's critical infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The federal department and agency plans were assimilated with the sector NIAPs to create one comprehensive National Infrastructure Assurance Plan.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Additionally the national structure must ensure there is a national CIP program.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This program includes responsibilities such as education and awareness, threat assessment and investigation, and research.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There have been public criticisms of the mechanisms and implementation of some security initiatives and grants, with claims they are being led by the same companies who can benefit, and that they are encouraging an unnecessary culture of fear.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Commentators note that these initiatives started directly after the collapse of the Cold War, raising the concern that this was simply a diversion of the military-industrial complex away from a funding area which was shrinking and into a richer previously civilian arena.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Grants have been distributed across the different states even though the perceived risk is not evenly spread, leading to accusations of pork barrel politics that directs money and jobs towards marginal voting areas.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The Urban Areas Security Initiative grant program has been particularly controversial, with the 2006 infrastructure list covering 77,000 assets, including a popcorn factory and a hot dog stand.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The 2007 criteria were reduced to 2,100 and now those facilities must make a much stronger case to become eligible for grants.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] While well-intentioned, some of the results have also been questioned regarding claims of poorly designed and intrusive security theater that distracts attention and money from more pressing issues or creates damaging side effects.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] An absence of comparative risk analysis and benefits tracking it has made it difficult to counter such allegations with authority.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In order to better understand this, and ultimately direct effort more productively, a Risk Management and Analysis Office was recently created in the National Protection and Programs directorate at the Department of Homeland Security.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Department of Defense is responsible for protecting its portion of the government's critical infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] But as part of the CIP program, DoD has responsibilities that traverse both the national and department-wide critical infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] PDD-63 identified the responsibilities DoD had for critical infrastructure protection.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] First, DoD had to identify its own critical assets and infrastructures and provide assurance through analysis, assessment, and remediation.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] DoD was also responsible for identifying and monitoring the national and international infrastructure requirements of industry and other government agencies, all of which needed to be included in the protection planning.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] DoD also addressed the assurance and protection of commercial assets and infrastructure services in DoD acquisitions.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Other DoD responsibilities for CIP included assessing the potential impact on military operations that would result from the loss or compromise of infrastructure service.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There were also requirements for monitoring DoD operations, detecting and responding to infrastructure incidents, and providing department indications and warnings as part of the national process.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Ultimately, DoD was responsible for supporting national critical infrastructure protection.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In response to the requirements identified in PDD-63, DoD categorized its own critical assets by sector, in a manner similar to the national CIP organization.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The DoD identified a slightly different list of infrastructure sectors for those areas that specifically required protection by DoD.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] DoD's organizational structure for critical infrastructure protection reflects, complements, and effectively interacts with the national structure for CIP.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There are ten defense critical infrastructure sectors that are protected by the DoD.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The DoD CIP special function components interface with the equivalent national functional coordinators and coordinate all activities related to their function within DoD.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] DoD's special function components currently include seven areas of focus.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] As mandated by PDD-63, the DoD must protect its portion of the federal government's critical infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] For DoD, this is the Defense Infrastructure or DI.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Protecting the Defense Infrastructure is a complex task involving ten defense sectors.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] It was deemed that it was nearly impossible to protect every critical asset at every location, therefore the focus was directed on protecting the critical Defense Infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The critical Defense Infrastructure is the critical assets essential to providing mission assurance.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The six phases of the DoD CIP life cycle build on one another to create a framework for a comprehensive solution for infrastructure assurance.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The life cycle phases occur before, during, and after an event that may compromise or degrade the infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Effective management of the CIP life cycle ensures that protection activities can be coordinated and reconciled among all DoD sectors.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] In many ways, DoD CIP, is risk management at its most imperative.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Achieving success means obtaining mission assurance.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Missing the mark can mean mission failure as well as human and material losses.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] For critical infrastructure protection, risk management requires leveraging resources to address the most critical infrastructure assets that are also the most vulnerable and that have the greatest threat exposure.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The most important part of the CIP lifecycle is Phase 1.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Because it is crucial to target the right assets for infrastructure protection, determining these assets is the first phase in the CIP life cycle.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] This phase, Analysis and Assessment, is the key and foundation of the seven lifecycle activities.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Without a solid foundation, the remaining CIP life cycle phases may be flawed, resulting in a CIP plan that fails to protect the critical infrastructure and, therefore, mission assurance.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Phase 1 determines what assets are important, and identifies their vulnerabilities, and dependencies so that decision makers have the information they need to make effective risk management choices.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The Defense Infrastructure, or DI, is organized into ten sectors.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Each sector is composed of assets, such as systems, programs, people, equipment, or facilities.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Assets may be simple, such as one facility within one geographic location, or complex, involving geographically dispersed links and nodes.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The Analysis and Assessment is made up of five steps that include activities that span and encompass the ten DI sectors and their assets.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] On August 24, 2001, the Director of the Joint Staff requested USPACOM to serve as the lead support Combatant Command for creating a CIP first-ever theater CIP Plan – known as the “CIP Appendix 16 Plan”.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The following is how USPACOM approached the task.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] To accomplish these steps, USPACOM adopted a methodology that focuses its CIP efforts on Tier 1 assets.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Tier 1 assets are assets that could cause mission failure if they are compromised or damaged.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The methodology UAPACOM adopted and modified is Mission Area Analysis, or MAA.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The MAA links combatant command missions to infrastructure assets that are critical to a given Operations Plan, or OPLAN, Contingency Plan, or CONPLAN, or Crisis Action Plan.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Typically, the MAA process determines the assessment site priorities.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] USPACOM modified the process and selected the CIP assessment sites and installations prior to conducting the MAA.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] USPACOM uses the MAA data it gathers to scope and focus its efforts on truly mission-critical assets to answer the next question in its process, Is it vulnerable?
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The first step in answering this question is to complete an installation analysis.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The next step is to complete a commercial infrastructure analysis.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] USPACOM relied upon two different DoD organizations for CIP assessments: Balanced Survivability Assessments, or BSAs, and Mission Assurance Assessments.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The BSA is a two-week mission-focused assessment at a military installation or designated site.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] A Mission Assurance Assessment is unique because it uses an area assessment approach to focus on both commercial and military asset vulnerabilities and dependencies.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The final step to determine vulnerabilities is to integrate the two analyses and assessments.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] With its critical assets and their vulnerabilities identified, USPACOM is ready to perform risk management activities to decide what can be done to protect the mission-critical assets.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Booz Allen Hamilton developed this process at PACOM.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The first phase of the CIP life cycle, Analysis and Assessment, identified the critical assets of DoD sector infrastructures and the vulnerabilities or weaknesses of those critical assets.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The second phase is the Remediation phase.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] In the Remediation phase, the known weaknesses and vulnerabilities are addressed.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Remediation actions are deliberate, precautionary measures designed to fix known virtual and physical vulnerabilities before an event occurs.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The purpose of remediation is to improve the reliability, availability, and survivability of critical assets and infrastructures.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Remediation actions apply to any type of vulnerability, regardless of its cause.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] They apply to acts of nature, technology failures, or deliberate malicious actions.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The cost of each remediation action depends on the nature of the vulnerability it addresses.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The Defense Infrastructure Sector Assurance Plan that each infrastructure sector must develop, establishes the priorities and resources for remediation.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Remediation requirements are determined by multiple factors.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These are analysis and assessment, input from military planners and other DoD sectors, the National Infrastructure Assurance Plan and other plans, reports, and information on national infrastructure vulnerabilities and remediation, as well as intelligence estimates and assessments of threats.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Remediation requirements are also gathered through lessons learned from Defense Infrastructure sector monitoring and reporting and infrastructure protection operations and exercises.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The CIP program tracks the status of remediation activities for critical assets.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Remediation activities to protect the critical Defense Infrastructure cross multiple Department components.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The need to monitor activities and warn of potential threats to the United States is not new.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] From conventional assaults to potential nuclear attacks, the military has been at the forefront of monitoring and warning of potential dangers since the founding of the country.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Protecting the security and well-being of the United States, including the critical Defense Infrastructure, has now entered a new era.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] It has been deemed essential to have a coordinated ability to identify and warn of potential or actual incidents among critical infrastructure domains.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The ability to detect and warn of infrastructure events is the third phase of the critical infrastructure protection life cycle, the Indications and Warnings phase.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Historically, DoD event indications have focused and relied on intelligence information about foreign developments.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These event indications have been expanded to include all potential infrastructure disruption or degradation, regardless of its cause.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] This fusion of traditional intelligence information with sector-specific information has been determined to be essential for meaningful CIP indications.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] If an indication is detected, a warning notifying the appropriate asset owners of a possible or occurring event or hazard can be issued.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The sector's assurance plan determines what conditions and actions are monitored and reported for each Defense Infrastructure Sector.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Each sector must develop a written Defense Sector Assurance Plan that includes a compendium of sector incidents for monitoring and reporting.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] DoD critical asset owners, installations, and sector CIAOs determine the DoD and sector-defined incidents.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The National Infrastructure Protection Center (NIPC) is the primary national warning center for significant infrastructure attacks.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Critical asset owners, DoD installations, and Sector CIAOs monitor the infrastructure daily.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Indications of an infrastructure incident are reported to the National Military Command Center, or NMCC.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] If indications are on a computer network, they are also reported to the Joint Task Force Computer Network Operations (JTF-CNO).
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The NMCC and JTF-CNO assess the indications and pass them to the NIPC and appropriate DoD organizations.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When the NIPC determines that an infrastructure event is likely to occur, is planned, or is under way, it issues a national warning.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] For DoD, the NIPC passes its warnings and alerts to the NMCC and JTF-CNO.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These warnings and alerts are then passed to the DoD components.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The warning may include guidance regarding additional protection measures DoD should take.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Phase 1 of the CIP life cycle provided a layer of protection by identifying and assessing critical assets and their vulnerabilities.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Phase 2 provided another layer of protection by remediating or improving the identified deficiencies and weaknesses of an asset.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Even with these protections and precautions, an infrastructure incident was still possible.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When it does the Indications and Warnings phase goes into effect.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The Mitigation phase (Phase 4), is made up of preplanned coordinated actions in response to infrastructure warnings or incidents.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Mitigation actions are taken before or during an infrastructure event.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These actions are designed to minimize the operational impact of the loss of a critical asset, facilitate incident response, and quickly restore the infrastructure service.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] A primary purpose of the Mitigation phase is to minimize the operational impact on other critical Defense Infrastructures and assets when a critical asset is lost or damaged.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] As an example, if there is a U.S. installation, Site A, located in a host nation.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Site A is a tier 1 asset, meaning that if it fails, the Combatant Commands mission fails.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Site A has mutual Global Information Grid Command Control (GIG/C2), information interdependencies with Sites B and C.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] In addition, other Defense Infrastructure sectors rely on Site A for mission capabilities.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] In this scenario, what could be the impact if the supply line to the commercial power plant that provides the installation's primary power is accidentally severed.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Because of all the interdependencies, losing this asset is more than the loss of just one site.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] It means the loss of other sector capabilities.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] A possible mitigation action might be for Site A to go on backup power.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] An alternate action could be to pass complete control of Site A's functionality to another site, where redundancy has been previously arranged.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These actions would limit the impact of this incident on the other sites and related sectors.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] In addition to lessening the operational impact of a critical infrastructure event, the Mitigation phase of the CIP life cycle supports and complements two other life cycle phases.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Mitigation actions aid in the emergency, investigation, and management activities of Phase 5, Incident Response.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] They also facilitate the reconstitution activities of Phase 6.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When there is a warning, emergency, or infrastructure incident, the critical asset owners, installations, and Sector CIAOs initiate mitigation actions to sustain service to the DoD.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] They also provide mitigation status information to the NMCC and JTF-CNO.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The NMCC monitors for consequences from an event within one Defense Infrastructure sector that are significant enough to affect other sectors.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] For events that cross two or more sectors, the NMCC advises on the prioritization and coordination of mitigation actions.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When event threats or consequences continue to escalate, the NMCC directs mitigation actions by sector to ensure a coordinated response across the DoD.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The NMCC and the JTF-CNO keep the National Infrastructure Protection Center, or NIPC, apprised of any significant mitigation activities.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When an event affects the Defense Infrastructure, the Incident Response phase begins.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Incident Response is the fifth phase of the CIP life cycle.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The purpose of the Incident Response phase is to eliminate the cause or source of an infrastructure event.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] For example, during the 9/11 attacks on the World Trade Center and Pentagon, all non-military airplanes were grounded over the United States to prevent further incidents.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Response activities included emergency measures, not from the asset owners or operators, but from dedicated third parties such as law enforcement, medical rescue, fire rescue, hazardous material or explosives handling, and investigative agencies.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Response to Defense Infrastructure incidents can take one of two paths depending on whether or not the event affects a DoD computer network.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When incidents compromise a DoD computer network, the Joint Task Force-Computer Network Operations (JTF-CNO) directs the response activities.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These activities are designed to stop the computer network attack, contain and mitigate damage to a DoD information network and then restore minimum required functionality.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] JTF-CNO also requests and coordinates any support or assistance from other Federal agencies and civilian organizations during incidents affecting a DoD network.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When incidents impact any other DoD owned assets, installation commanders and critical asset owners follow traditional channels and procedures to coordinate responses.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] This includes notifying affected Sector Chief Infrastructure Assurance Officers, or CIAOs, in the initial notice and status reporting.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Although third parties play a major role in the response to Defense Infrastructure events, DoD CIP personnel also have responsibilities to fulfill.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] After the source or cause of an infrastructure event is eliminated or contained, the infrastructure and its capabilities must be restored.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Reconstitution is the last phase of the critical infrastructure protection.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Reconstitution is probably the most challenging and least developed process of the life cycle.
[src:ot-security-ics/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] DoD critical asset owners have the major responsibility for reconstitution.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] A **distributed control system** (**DCS**) is a computerized control system for a process or plant usually with many control loops, in which autonomous controllers are distributed throughout the system, but there is no central operator supervisory control.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] This is in contrast to systems that use centralized controllers; either discrete controllers located at a central control room or within a central computer.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The DCS concept increases reliability and reduces installation costs by localizing control functions near the process plant, with remote monitoring and supervision.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems first emerged in large, high value, safety critical process industries, and were attractive because the DCS manufacturer would supply both the local control level and central supervisory equipment as an integrated package, thus reducing design integration risk.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Today the functionality of Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) and DCS systems are very similar, but DCS tends to be used on large continuous process plants where high reliability and security is important, and the control room is not necessarily geographically remote.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Many machine control systems exhibit similar properties as plant and process control systems do.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The key attribute of a DCS is its reliability due to the distribution of the control processing around nodes in the system.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] This mitigates a single processor failure.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] If a processor fails, it will only affect one section of the plant process, as opposed to a failure of a central computer which would affect the whole process.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] This distribution of computing power local to the field Input/Output (I/O) connection racks also ensures fast controller processing times by removing possible network and central processing delays.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels using computerised control.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Levels 1 and 2 are the functional levels of a traditional DCS, in which all equipment are part of an integrated system from a single manufacturer.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Levels 3 and 4 are not strictly process control in the traditional sense, but where production control and scheduling takes place.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The processor nodes and operator graphical displays are connected over proprietary or industry standard networks, and network reliability is increased by dual redundancy cabling over diverse routes.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] This distributed topology also reduces the amount of field cabling by siting the I/O modules and their associated processors close to the process plant.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be signalled by the output modules.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can be analog signals e.g.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] 4–20 mA DC current loop or two-state signals that switch either "on" or "off", such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] DCSs are connected to sensors and actuators and use setpoint control to control the flow of material through the plant.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] A typical application is a PID controller fed by a flow meter and using a control valve as the final control element.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The DCS sends the setpoint required by the process to the controller which instructs a valve to operate so that the process reaches and stays at the desired setpoint.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Large oil refineries and chemical plants have several thousand I/O points and employ very large DCS.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Processes are not limited to fluidic flow through pipes, however, and can also include things like paper machines and their associated quality controls, variable speed drives and motor control centers, cement kilns, mining operations, ore processing facilities, and many others.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] DCSs in very high reliability applications can have dual redundant processors with "hot" switch over on fault, to enhance the reliability of the control system.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Although 4–20 mA has been the main field signalling standard, modern DCS systems can also support fieldbus digital protocols, such as Foundation Fieldbus, profibus, HART, modbus, PC Link, etc.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Modern DCSs also support neural networks and fuzzy logic applications.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Recent research focuses on the synthesis of optimal distributed controllers, which optimizes a certain H-infinity or the H 2 control criterion.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems (DCS) are dedicated systems used in manufacturing processes that are continuous or batch-oriented.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] However this required a large amount of human oversight to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Effectively this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] These could be distributed around plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The distributed control system was born.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Early minicomputers were used in the control of industrial processes since the beginning of the 1960s.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The IBM 1800, for example, was an early computer that had input/output hardware to gather process signals in a plant for conversion from field contact levels (for digital points) and analog signals to the digital domain.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The first industrial control computer system was built 1959 at the Texaco Port Arthur, Texas, refinery with an RW-300 of the Ramo-Wooldridge Company.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] In 1975, both HONEYWELL and Japanese electrical engineering firm Yokogawa introduced their own independently produced DCS's - TDC 2000 and CENTUM systems, respectively.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] US-based Bristol also introduced their UCS 3000 universal controller in 1975.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] In 1978 Valmet introduced their own DCS system called Damatic (latest web-based generation Valmet DNAe).
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] In 1980, Bailey (now part of ABB) introduced the NETWORK 90 system, Fisher Controls (now part of Emerson Electric) introduced the PROVoX system, Fischer & Porter Company (now also part of ABB) introduced DCI-4000 (DCI stands for Distributed Control Instrumentation).
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The DCS largely came about due to the increased availability of microcomputers and the proliferation of microprocessors in the world of process control.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Computers had already been applied to process automation for some time in the form of both direct digital control (DDC) and setpoint control.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] In the early 1970s Taylor Instrument Company, (now part of ABB) developed the 1010 system, Foxboro the FOX1 system, Fisher Controls the DC2 system and Bailey Controls the 1055 systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] All of these were DDC applications implemented within minicomputers (DEC PDP-11, Varian Data Machines, MODCOMP etc.) and connected to proprietary Input/Output hardware.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Sophisticated (for the time) continuous as well as batch control was implemented in this way.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] A more conservative approach was setpoint control, where process computers supervised clusters of analog process controllers.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] A workstation provided visibility into the process using text and crude character graphics.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Availability of a fully functional graphical user interface was a way away.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Central to the DCS model was the inclusion of control function blocks.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Function blocks evolved from early, more primitive DDC concepts of "Table Driven" software.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] One of the first embodiments of object-oriented software, function blocks were self-contained "blocks" of code that emulated analog hardware control components and performed tasks that were essential to process control, such as execution of PID algorithms.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Function blocks continue to endure as the predominant method of control for DCS suppliers, and are supported by key technologies such as Foundation Fieldbus today.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Midac Systems, of Sydney, Australia, developed an objected-oriented distributed direct digital control system in 1982.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The central system ran 11 microprocessors sharing tasks and common memory and connected to a serial communication network of distributed controllers each running two Z80s.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The system was installed at the University of Melbourne.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Digital communication between distributed controllers, workstations and other computing elements (peer to peer access) was one of the primary advantages of the DCS.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Attention was duly focused on the networks, which provided the all-important lines of communication that, for process applications, had to incorporate specific functions such as determinism and redundancy.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] As a result, many suppliers embraced the IEEE 802.4 networking standard.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] This decision set the stage for the wave of migrations necessary when information technology moved into process automation and IEEE 802.3 rather than IEEE 802.4 prevailed as the control LAN.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] In the 1980s, users began to look at DCSs as more than just basic process control.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] A very early example of a Direct Digital Control DCS was completed by the Australian business Midac in 1981–82 using R-Tec Australian designed hardware.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The system installed at the University of Melbourne used a serial communications network, connecting campus buildings back to a control room "front end".
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Each remote unit ran two Z80 microprocessors, while the front end ran eleven Z80s in a parallel processing configuration with paged common memory to share tasks and that could run up to 20,000 concurrent control objects.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] It was believed that if openness could be achieved and greater amounts of data could be shared throughout the enterprise that even greater things could be achieved.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The first attempts to increase the openness of DCSs resulted in the adoption of the predominant operating system of the day: *UNIX*.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] UNIX and its companion networking technology TCP-IP were developed by the US Department of Defense for openness, which was precisely the issue the process industries were looking to resolve.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] As a result, suppliers also began to adopt Ethernet-based networks with their own proprietary protocol layers.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The full TCP/IP standard was not implemented, but the use of Ethernet made it possible to implement the first instances of object management and global data access technology.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The 1980s also witnessed the first PLCs integrated into the DCS infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Plant-wide historians also emerged to capitalize on the extended reach of automation systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The first DCS supplier to adopt UNIX and Ethernet networking technologies was Foxboro, who introduced the I/A Series system in 1987.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The drive toward openness in the 1980s gained momentum through the 1990s with the increased adoption of commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) components and IT standards.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Probably the biggest transition undertaken during this time was the move from the UNIX operating system to the Windows environment.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] While the realm of the real time operating system (RTOS) for control applications remains dominated by real time commercial variants of UNIX or proprietary operating systems, everything above real-time control has made the transition to Windows.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The introduction of Microsoft at the desktop and server layers resulted in the development of technologies such as OLE for process control (OPC), which is now a de facto industry connectivity standard.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Internet technology also began to make its mark in automation and the world, with most DCS HMI supporting Internet connectivity.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The 1990s were also known for the "Fieldbus Wars", where rival organizations competed to define what would become the IEC fieldbus standard for digital communication with field instrumentation instead of 4–20 milliamp analog communications.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The first fieldbus installations occurred in the 1990s.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Towards the end of the decade, the technology began to develop significant momentum, with the market consolidated around Ethernet I/P, Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA for process automation applications.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Fieldbus technics have been used to integrate machine, drives, quality and condition monitoring applications to one DCS with Valmet DNA system.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The impact of COTS, however, was most pronounced at the hardware layer.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] For years, the primary business of DCS suppliers had been the supply of large amounts of hardware, particularly I/O and controllers.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The initial proliferation of DCSs required the installation of prodigious amounts of this hardware, most of it manufactured from the bottom up by DCS suppliers.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Standard computer components from manufacturers such as Intel and Motorola, however, made it cost prohibitive for DCS suppliers to continue making their own components, workstations, and networking hardware.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] As the suppliers made the transition to COTS components, they also discovered that the hardware market was shrinking fast.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] COTS not only resulted in lower manufacturing costs for the supplier, but also steadily decreasing prices for the end users, who were also becoming increasingly vocal over what they perceived to be unduly high hardware costs.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The traditional DCS suppliers introduced new generation DCS System based on the latest Communication and IEC Standards, which resulting in a trend of combining the traditional concepts/functionalities for PLC and DCS into a one for all solution—named "Process Automation System" (PAS).
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The gaps among the various systems remain at the areas such as: the database integrity, pre-engineering functionality, system maturity, communication transparency and reliability.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] While it is expected the cost ratio is relatively the same (the more powerful the systems are, the more expensive they will be), the reality of the automation business is often operating strategically case by case.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The current next evolution step is called Collaborative Process Automation Systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] To compound the issue, suppliers were also realizing that the hardware market was becoming saturated.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The life cycle of hardware components such as I/O and wiring is also typically in the range of 15 to over 20 years, making for a challenging replacement market.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Many of the older systems that were installed in the 1970s and 1980s are still in use today, and there is a considerable installed base of systems in the market that are approaching the end of their useful life.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Developed industrial economies in North America, Europe, and Japan already had many thousands of DCSs installed, and with few if any new plants being built, the market for new hardware was shifting rapidly to smaller, albeit faster growing regions such as China, Latin America, and Eastern Europe.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Because of the shrinking hardware business, suppliers began to make the challenging transition from a hardware-based business model to one based on software and value-added services.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] It is a transition that is still being made today.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The applications portfolio offered by suppliers expanded considerably in the '90s to include areas such as production management, model-based control, real-time optimization, plant asset management (PAM), Real-time performance management (RPM) tools, alarm management, and many others.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] To obtain the true value from these applications, however, often requires a considerable service content, which the suppliers also provide.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Increasingly, and ironically, DCS are becoming centralised at plant level, with the ability to log into the remote equipment.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] This enables operator to control both at enterprise level ( macro ) and at the equipment level (micro), both within and outside the plant, because the importance of the physical location drops due to interconnectivity primarily thanks to wireless and remote access.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] The more wireless protocols are developed and refined, the more they are included in DCS.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] DCS controllers are now often equipped with embedded servers and provide on-the-go web access.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Whether DCS will lead Industrial Internet of Things (IIOT) or borrow key elements from remains to be seen.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] Many vendors provide the option of a mobile HMI, ready for both Android and iOS.
[src:ot-security-ics/distributed-control-system] With these interfaces, the threat of security breaches and possible damage to plant and process are now very real.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] An **industrial control system** (**ICS**) is an electronic control system and associated instrumentation used for industrial process control.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Control systems can range in size from a few modular panel-mounted controllers to large interconnected and interactive distributed control systems (DCSs) with many thousands of field connections.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Control systems receive data from remote sensors measuring process variables (PVs), compare the collected data with desired setpoints (SPs), and derive command functions that are used to control a process through the final control elements (FCEs), such as control valves.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Larger systems are usually implemented by supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems, or DCSs, and programmable logic controllers (PLCs), though SCADA and PLC systems are scalable down to small systems with few control loops.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Such systems are extensively used in industries such as chemical processing, pulp and paper manufacture, power generation, oil and gas processing, and telecommunications.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The simplest control systems are based around small discrete controllers with a single control loop each.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] These are usually panel mounted, which allows direct viewing of the front panel and provides a means of manual intervention by the operator, either to manually control the process or to change control setpoints.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Originally, these would be pneumatic controllers, a few of which are still in use, but nearly all are now electronic.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Quite complex systems can be created with networks of these controllers communicating using industry-standard protocols.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Networking allows the use of local or remote SCADA operator interfaces and enables the cascading and interlocking of controllers.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] However, as the number of control loops increases for a system design, there is a point where the use of a programmable logic controller (PLC) or distributed control system (DCS) is more manageable or cost-effective.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] A distributed control system (DCS) is a digital process control system (PCS) for a process or plant, wherein controller functions and field connection modules are distributed throughout the system.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] As the number of control loops grows, DCS becomes more cost effective than discrete controllers.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Additionally, a DCS provides supervisory viewing and management over large industrial processes.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] In a DCS, a hierarchy of controllers is connected by communication networks, allowing centralized control rooms and local on-plant monitoring and control.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] A DCS enables easy configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other computer systems such as production control.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] It also enables more sophisticated alarm handling, introduces automatic event logging, removes the need for physical records such as chart recorders and allows the control equipment to be networked and thereby located locally to the equipment being controlled to reduce cabling.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] A DCS typically uses custom-designed processors as controllers and uses either proprietary interconnections or standard protocols for communication.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Input and output modules form the peripheral components of the system.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be performed by the output modules.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The input modules receive information from sensing instruments in the process (or field) and the output modules transmit instructions to the final control elements, such as control valves.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can either be continuously changing analog signals, e.g., current loop or 2-state signals that switch either *on* or *off*, such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Distributed control systems can normally also support Foundation Fieldbus, PROFIBUS, HART, Modbus and other digital communication buses that carry not only input and output signals but also advanced messages such as error diagnostics and status signals.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) is a control system architecture that uses computers, networked data communications and graphical user interfaces for high-level process supervisory management.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA supervisory computer system.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] However, the real-time control logic or controller calculations are performed by networked modules which connect to other peripheral devices such as programmable logic controllers and discrete PID controllers which interface to the process plant or machinery.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The SCADA concept was developed as a universal means of remote access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers, allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become very similar to distributed control systems in function, but using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] They can control large-scale processes that can include multiple sites and work over large distances.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] This is a commonly used architecture industrial control systems, however there are concerns about SCADA systems being vulnerable to cyberwarfare or cyberterrorism attacks.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The SCADA software operates on a supervisory level as control actions are performed automatically by RTUs or PLCs.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] SCADA control functions are usually restricted to basic overriding or supervisory level intervention.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] A feedback control loop is directly controlled by the RTU or PLC, but the SCADA software monitors the overall performance of the loop.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] For example, a PLC may control the flow of cooling water through part of an industrial process to a set point level, but the SCADA system software will allow operators to change the set points for the flow.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The SCADA also enables alarm conditions, such as loss of flow or high temperature, to be displayed and recorded.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O) in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Initially, control was from panels local to the process plant.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] However, this required personnel to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently staffed central control room.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Often, the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were individually transmitted back to the plant in the form of pneumatic or electrical signals.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Effectively, this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of reduced manpower requirements and a consolidated overview of the process.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, so system changes required reconfiguration of signals by re-piping or re-wiring.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] It also required continual operator movement within a large control room in order to monitor the whole process.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors, high-speed electronic signalling networks and electronic graphic displays, it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] These could be distributed around the plant and would communicate with the graphic displays in the control room.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The concept of *distributed control* was realised.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The introduction of distributed control allowed flexible interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] For large control systems, the general commercial name *distributed control system* (DCS) was coined to refer to proprietary modular systems from many manufacturers that integrated high-speed networking and a full suite of displays and control racks.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] While the DCS was tailored to meet the needs of large continuous industrial processes, in industries where combinatorial and sequential logic was the primary requirement, the PLC evolved out of a need to replace racks of relays and timers used for event-driven control.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The old controls were difficult to reconfigure and debug, and PLC control enabled networking of signals to a central control area with electronic displays.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] PLCs were first developed for the automotive industry on vehicle production lines, where sequential logic was becoming very complex.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] It was soon adopted in a large number of other event-driven applications as varied as printing presses and water treatment plants.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] SCADA's history is rooted in distribution applications, such as power, natural gas, and water pipelines, where there is a need to gather remote data through potentially unreliable or intermittent low-bandwidth and high-latency links.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] SCADA systems use open-loop control with sites that are widely separated geographically.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] A SCADA system uses remote terminal units (RTUs) to send supervisory data back to a control centre.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Most RTU systems always had some capacity to handle local control while the master station is not available.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] However, over the years, RTU systems have grown more and more capable of handling local control.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The boundaries between DCS and SCADA/PLC systems are blurring as time goes on.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The technical limits that drove the designs of these various systems are no longer as much of an issue.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Many PLC platforms can now perform quite well as a small DCS, using remote I/O and are sufficiently reliable that some SCADA systems actually manage closed-loop control over long distances.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] With the increasing speed of today's processors, many DCS products have a full line of PLC-like subsystems that weren't offered when they were initially developed.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] In 1993, with the release of IEC-1131, later to become IEC-61131-3, the industry moved towards increased code standardization with reusable, hardware-independent control software.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] For the first time, object-oriented programming (OOP) became possible within industrial control systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] This led to the development of both programmable automation controllers (PAC) and industrial PCs (IPC).
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] These are platforms programmed in the five standardized IEC languages: ladder logic, structured text, function block, instruction list and sequential function chart.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] They can also be programmed in modern high-level languages such as C or C++.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Additionally, they accept models developed in analytical tools such as MATLAB and Simulink.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Unlike traditional PLCs, which use proprietary operating systems, IPCs utilize Windows IoT.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] IPCs have the advantage of powerful multi-core processors with much lower hardware costs than traditional PLCs and fit well into multiple form factors such as DIN rail mount, combined with a touch-screen as a panel PC, or as an embedded PC.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] New hardware platforms and technology have contributed significantly to the evolution of DCS and SCADA systems, further blurring the boundaries and changing definitions.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] SCADA and PLCs are vulnerable to cyber attack.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] Government Joint Capability Technology Demonstration (JCTD) known as MOSAICS (More Situational Awareness for Industrial Control Systems) is the initial demonstration of cybersecurity defensive capability for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] MOSAICS addresses the Department of Defense (DOD) operational need for cyber defense capabilities to defend critical infrastructure control systems from cyber attack, such as power, water and wastewater, and safety controls, affect the physical environment.
[src:ot-security-ics/industrial-control-system] The MOSAICS JCTD prototype will be shared with commercial industry through Industry Days for further research and development, an approach intended to lead to an innovative, game-changing capabilities for cybersecurity for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] The built environment, whether commercial or domestic, is increasingly controlled and monitored via Internet of Things (IoT) and Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) devices.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] In this application space, these IoT devices are both interconnected via converged technology edge IoT platforms and or via "cloud" based applications.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Embedded Systems are also included in the sphere of operational technology (e.g. smart instrumentation), along with a large subset of scientific data acquisition, control, and computing devices.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Systems that process operational data (including electronic, telecommunications, computer systems and technical components) are included under the term operational technology.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] OT systems can be required to control valves, engines, conveyors and other machines to regulate various process values, such as temperature, pressure, flow, and to monitor them to prevent hazardous conditions.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] OT systems use various technologies for hardware design and communications protocols, that are unknown in IT.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Common problems include supporting legacy systems & devices and numerous vendor architectures and standards.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Since OT systems often supervise industrial processes, most of the time availability must be sustained.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] This often means that real time (or near-real time) processing is required, with high rates of reliability and availability.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] This kind of environment may also be referred to as industrial information technology (IIT).
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Historical OT networks utilized proprietary protocols optimized for the required functions, some of which have become adopted as 'standard' industrial communications protocols (e.g.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] DNP3, Modbus, Profibus, LonWorks, DALI, BACnet, KNX, EnOcean and OPC-UA).
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] More recently IT-standard network protocols are being implemented in OT devices and systems to reduce complexity and increase compatibility with more traditional IT hardware (e.g.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] TCP/IP); this however has had a demonstrable reduction in security for OT systems, which in the past have relied on air gaps and the inability to run PC-based malware (see Stuxnet for a well-known example of this change).
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] The term operational technology as applied to industrial control systems was first published in a research paper from Gartner in May 2006 (Steenstrup, Sumic, Spiers, Williams) and presented publicly in September 2006 at the Gartner Energy and Utilities IT Summit.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Initially the term was applied to power utility control systems, but over time was adopted by other industrial sectors and used in combination with IoT.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] A principal driver of the adoption of the term was that the nature of operational technology platforms had evolved from bespoke proprietary systems to complex software portfolios that rely on IT infrastructure.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] This change was termed IT OT convergence.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] The concept of aligning and integrating the IT and OT systems of industrial companies gained importance as companies realized that physical assets and infrastructure was both managed by OT systems but also generated data for the IT systems running the business.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Industrial technology companies such as GE, Hitachi, Honeywell, Siemens, ABB and Rockwell are the main providers of OT platforms and systems either embedded in equipment or added to them for control, management and monitoring.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] These industrial technology companies have needed to evolve into software companies rather than being strictly machine providers.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Security of operational technology systems has historically relied almost entirely on the standalone nature of OT installations, security by obscurity.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] At least since 2005 OT systems have become linked to IT systems with the corporate goal of widening an organization's ability to monitor and adjust its OT systems, which has introduced massive challenges in securing them.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Approaches known from regular IT are usually replaced or redesigned to align with the OT environment.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] The intersection of operational technology and standard networking infrastructure exposes industrial processes to several distinct categories of risk.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Mitigation of these integrated risks typically involves the adoption of multi-layered security frameworks, continuous anomaly monitoring, and adherence to established institutional standards such as the ISA/IEC 62443 series.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Operational technology is widely used in refineries, power plants, nuclear plants, etc. and as such has become a common, crucial element of critical infrastructure systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] Depending on the country, critical infrastructure operators may face increasing legal obligations with regard to the implementation of OT systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] For several decades, hundreds of thousands of buildings have been upgraded with IoT building management, automation and smart lighting control solutions, but many of these solutions lack the proper security measures.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] This has recently led to bad actors exploiting such solutions' vulnerabilities with ransomware attacks causing system lock outs, operational failures exposing businesses operating in such buildings to the immense risks to health and safety, operations, brand reputation and financial damage.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] There is a strong focus put on subjects like IT/OT cooperation or IT/OT alignment in the modern industrial setting.
[src:ot-security-ics/operational-technology] The Stuxnet malware is one example of this, highlighting the potential for disaster should a safety system become infected with malware (whether targeted at that system or accidentally infected).
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O), in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] They can be designed for many arrangements of digital and analog I/O, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs were first developed in the automobile manufacturing industry to provide flexible, rugged and easily programmable controllers to replace hard-wired relay logic systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Dick Morley, who invented the first PLC, the Modicon 084, for General Motors in 1968, is considered the father of PLC.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an example of a hard real-time system since output results must be produced in response to input conditions within a limited time, otherwise unintended operation may result.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC originated in the late 1960s in the automotive industry in the US and was designed to replace relay logic systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Before, control logic for manufacturing was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The hard-wired nature of these components made it difficult for design engineers to alter the automation process.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Changes would require rewiring and careful updating of the documentation.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] When general-purpose computers became available, they were soon applied to control logic in industrial processes.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] These early computers were unreliable and required specialist programmers and strict control of working conditions, such as temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC provided several advantages over earlier automation systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] It was designed to tolerate the industrial environment better than systems intended for office use, and was more reliable, compact, and required less maintenance than relay systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] It was easily expandable with additional I/O modules.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] While relay systems required tedious and sometimes complicated hardware changes in case of reconfiguration, a PLC can be reconfigured by loading new or modified code.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] This allowed for easier iteration over manufacturing process design.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] With a simple programming language focused on logic and switching operations, it was more user-friendly than computers using general-purpose programming languages.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Early PLCs were programmed in ladder logic, which strongly resembled a schematic diagram of relay logic.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] It also permitted its operation to be monitored.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] In recent years, the introduction of virtual PLCs has expanded the scope of programmable logic controllers.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Virtual PLCs are software-based controllers that simulate the functions of traditional PLCs but are executed on general-purpose hardware, offering a more cost-effective and flexible alternative.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] These controllers enable automation systems to be managed without the need for dedicated hardware, making them ideal for applications requiring simulation, remote control, or cloud-based systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] In 1968, GM Hydramatic, the automatic transmission division of General Motors, issued a request for proposals for an electronic replacement for hard-wired relay systems based on a white paper written by engineer Edward R.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The winning proposal came from Bedford Associates from Bedford, Massachusetts.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The result, built in 1969, was the first PLC and designated the *084*, because it was Bedford Associates' eighty-fourth project.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Bedford Associates started a company, **Modicon, Inc.**, dedicated to developing, manufacturing, selling, and servicing this new product, which they named **Modicon** (standing for "modular digital controller").
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] One of the people who worked on that project was Dick Morley, who is considered to be the father of the PLC.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The Modicon brand was sold in 1977 to Gould Electronics and later to Schneider Electric, its current owner.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] About this same time, Modicon created Modbus, a data communications protocol to be used with its PLCs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Modbus has since become a standard open protocol commonly used to connect many industrial electrical devices.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] One of the first Modicon 084 models built is now on display at Schneider Electric's facility in North Andover, Massachusetts.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] It was presented to Modicon by GM, when the unit was retired after nearly twenty years of uninterrupted service.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Modicon used the 84 moniker at the end of its product range like Modicon Micro 84 and Modicon TSX CSY 84 until after the 984 made its appearance.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] In a parallel development, Odo Josef Struger is sometimes known as the "father of the programmable logic controller" as well.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] He was involved in the invention of the Allen-Bradley programmable logic controller.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the release of the IBM "Personal Computer" in 1981, these devices were commonly known simply as "Programmable Controllers", or "PC's.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] But rapid expansion of the personal computer industry in the early 1980's, the abbreviation "PC" was rapidly and universally accepted as a reference to "Personal Computers".
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Odo was later credited with coining the "PLC" acronym to distinguish these two technologies, And the inclusion of the word "Logic" was an easy choice as "Ladder Logic" had already been accepted as the name of the programming language.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley (now a brand owned by Rockwell Automation) went on to become the dominant PLC manufacturer in the United States during his tenure.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Struger played a leadership role in developing IEC 61131-3 PLC programming language standards.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley's PLC-5 family, preceded by the 1774-PLC (released in the 1980's, was the first modular design found in modern-day systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] While Modicon was the most popular of the first full featured PLC's through the early 1980's, Allen Bradley overtook them in the mid-1980's and grew to own the largest market share of PLC hardware and software in North America.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Many early PLC programming applications were not capable of graphical representation of the logic, and so it was instead represented as a series of logic expressions in some kind of Boolean format, similar to Boolean algebra.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] As programming terminals evolved, because ladder logic was a familiar format used for electro-mechanical control panels, it became more commonly used.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Newer formats, such as state logic, function block diagrams, and structured text exist.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Ladder logic remains popular because PLCs solve the logic in a predictable and repeating sequence, and ladder logic allows the person writing the logic to see any issues with the timing of the logic sequence more easily than would be possible in other formats.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Up to the mid-1990s, PLCs were programmed using proprietary programming panels or special-purpose programming terminals, which often had dedicated function keys representing the various logical elements of PLC programs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Some proprietary programming terminals displayed the elements of PLC programs as graphic symbols, but plain ASCII character representations of contacts, coils, and wires were common.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Programs were stored on cassette tape cartridges.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Facilities for printing and documentation were minimal due to a lack of memory capacity.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The oldest PLCs used magnetic-core memory.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an industrial microprocessor-based controller with programmable memory used to store program instructions and various functions.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs require a programming device that is used to develop and later download the created program into the memory of the controller.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs generally contain a real-time operating system, such as OS-9 or VxWorks.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] There are two types of mechanical design for PLC systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] A *single box* (also called a *brick*) is a small programmable controller that fits all units and interfaces into one compact casing, although, typically, additional expansion modules for inputs and outputs are available.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The second design type – a *modular* PLC – has a chassis (also called a *rack*) that provides space for modules with different functions, such as power supply, processor, selection of I/O modules and communication interfaces – which all can be customized for the particular application.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Several racks can be administered by a single processor and may have thousands of inputs and outputs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Either a special high-speed serial I/O link or comparable communication method is used so that racks can be distributed away from the processor, reducing the wiring costs for large plants.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Discrete (digital) signals can only take *on* or *off* value (1 or 0, *true* or *false*).
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Examples of devices providing a discrete signal include limit switches and photoelectric sensors.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Analog signals can use voltage or current that is analogous to the monitored variable and can take any value within their scale.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Pressure, temperature, flow, and weight are often represented by analog signals.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically interpreted as integer values with various ranges of accuracy depending on the device and the number of bits available to store the data.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] For example, an analog 0 to 10 V or 4-20 mA current loop input would be converted into an integer value of 0 to 32,767.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC will take this value and translate it into the desired units of the process so the operator or program can read it.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Some special processes need to work permanently with minimum unwanted downtime.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Therefore, it is necessary to design a system that is fault tolerant.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] In such cases, to increase the system availability in the event of hardware component failure, redundant CPU or I/O modules with the same functionality can be added to a hardware configuration to prevent a total or partial process shutdown due to hardware failure.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Other redundancy scenarios could be related to safety-critical processes, for example, large hydraulic presses could require that two PLCs turn on an output before the press can come down in case one PLC does not behave properly.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Programmable logic controllers are intended to be used by engineers without a programming background.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] For this reason, a graphical programming language called ladder logic was first developed.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] It resembles the schematic diagram of a system built with electromechanical relays and was adopted by many manufacturers and later standardized in the IEC 61131-3 control systems programming standard.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, it is still widely used, thanks to its simplicity.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, the majority of PLC systems adhere to the IEC 61131-3 standard that defines two textual programming languages: Structured Text (similar to Pascal) and Instruction List; as well as three graphical languages: ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Instruction List was deprecated in the third edition of the standard.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs can be programmed in a variety of ways, from the relay-derived ladder logic to programming languages such as specially adapted dialects of BASIC and C.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] While the fundamental concepts of PLC programming are common to all manufacturers, differences in I/O addressing, memory organization, and instruction sets mean that PLC programs are never perfectly interchangeable between different makers.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Even within the same product line of a single manufacturer, different models may not be directly compatible.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Manufacturers develop programming software for their PLCs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] In addition to being able to program PLCs in multiple languages, they provide common features like hardware diagnostics and maintenance, software debugging, and offline simulation.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLC programs are typically written in a programming device, which can take the form of a desktop console, special software on a personal computer, or a handheld device.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The program is then downloaded to the PLC through a cable connection or over a network.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] It is stored either in non-volatile flash memory or battery-backed-up RAM on the PLC.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] In some PLCs, the program is transferred from the programming device using a programming board that writes the program into a removable chip, such as EPROM, that is then inserted into the PLC.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] An incorrectly programmed PLC can result in lost productivity and dangerous conditions for programmed equipment.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLC simulation is a feature often found in PLC programming software.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] It allows for testing and debugging early in a project's development.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Testing the project in simulation improves its quality, increases the level of safety associated with equipment and can save time during the installation and commissioning of automated control applications since many scenarios can be tried and tested before the system is activated.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The main difference compared to most other computing devices is that PLCs are intended for and therefore tolerant of more severe environmental conditions (such as dust, moisture, heat, cold), while offering extensive input/output (I/O) to connect the PLC to sensors and actuators.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLC input can include simple digital elements such as limit switches, analog variables from process sensors (such as temperature and pressure), and more complex data such as that from positioning or machine vision systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLC output can include elements such as indicator lamps, sirens, electric motors, pneumatic or hydraulic cylinders, magnetic relays, solenoids, or analog outputs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The input/output arrangements may be built into a simple PLC, or the PLC may have external I/O modules attached to a fieldbus or computer network that plugs into the PLC.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The functionality of the PLC has evolved over the years to include sequential relay control, motion control, process control, distributed control systems, and networking.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The data handling, storage, processing power, and communication capabilities of some modern PLCs are approximately equivalent to desktop computers.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLC-like programming combined with remote I/O hardware allows a general-purpose desktop computer to serve as a PLC in certain applications.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The most basic function of a programmable logic controller is to emulate the functions of electromechanical relays.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Within the PLC programming environment, discrete inputs are given a unique address, and a PLC instruction can test if the input state is on or off.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Just as a series of relay contacts performs a logical AND function, not allowing current to pass unless all the contacts are closed, so a series of *examine if on* instructions will energize its output storage bit if all the input bits are on.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Similarly, a parallel set of instructions will perform a logical OR.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] In an electromechanical relay wiring diagram, a group of contacts controlling one coil is called a *rung* of a *ladder diagram*, and this concept is also used to describe PLC logic.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The output of each rung sets or clears a storage bit, which may be associated with a discrete output or which may be an *internal coil* with no physical connection.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Such internal coils can be used, for example, as a common element in multiple separate rungs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] More advanced instructions of the PLC may be implemented as functional blocks, which carry out some operation, such as manipulating an internal variable, when enabled by a logical input and which produce outputs to signal, for example, completion or errors.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs use built-in ports, such as USB, Ethernet, RS-232, RS-485, or RS-422 to communicate with external devices (sensors, actuators) and systems (programming tools, SCADA and other user interfaces).
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Communication is carried over various industrial network protocols, like Modbus, or EtherNet/IP.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Many of these protocols are vendor specific.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Formerly, some manufacturers offered dedicated communication modules as an add-on function where the processor had no network connection built in.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs used in larger I/O systems may have peer-to-peer (P2P) communication between processors.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] This allows separate parts of a complex process to have individual control while allowing the subsystems to coordinate over the communication link.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs may need to interact with people for the purpose of configuration, alarm reporting, or everyday control.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] A human-machine interface (HMI) is employed for this purpose.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] HMIs are also referred to as man-machine interfaces (MMIs) and graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] A simple system may use buttons and lights to interact with the user.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Text displays are available as well as graphical touch screens.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] More complex systems use programming and monitoring software installed on a computer, with the PLC connected via a communication interface.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC works in a program scan cycle, where it executes its program repeatedly.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The program follows the sequence of instructions.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] It typically takes a time span of tens of milliseconds for the processor to evaluate all the instructions and update the status of all outputs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] If the system contains remote I/O—for example, an external rack with I/O modules—then that introduces additional uncertainty in the response time of the PLC system.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Special-purpose I/O modules may be used where the scan time of the PLC is too long to allow predictable performance.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Precision timing modules, or counter modules for use with shaft encoders, are used where the scan time would be too long to reliably count pulses or detect the sense of rotation of an encoder.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] This allows even a relatively slow PLC to still interpret the counted values to control a machine, as the accumulation of pulses is done by a dedicated module that is unaffected by the speed of program execution.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] As PLCs became more advanced, methods were developed to change the sequence of ladder execution, and subroutines were implemented.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the discovery of the Stuxnet computer worm in June 2010, the security of PLCs received little attention.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Modern programmable controllers generally contain real-time operating systems, which can be vulnerable to exploits in a similar way as desktop operating systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can also be attacked by gaining control of a computer they communicate with.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Since 2011, these concerns have grown as networking is becoming more commonplace in the PLC environment, connecting the previously separated plant floor networks and office networks.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] In February 2021, Rockwell Automation publicly disclosed a critical vulnerability affecting its Logix controller family.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The secret cryptographic key used to verify communication between the PLC and workstation could be extracted from the programming software (Studio 5000 Logix Designer) and used to remotely change program code and configuration of a connected controller.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The vulnerability was given a severity score of 10 out of 10 on the Common Vulnerability Scoring System.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Safety PLCs can be either a standalone device or safety-rated hardware and functionality added to existing controller architectures (Allen-Bradley GuardLogix, Siemens F-series, etc.).
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] These differ from conventional PLC types by being suitable for safety-critical applications for which PLCs have traditionally been supplemented with hard-wired safety relays and areas of the memory dedicated to the safety instructions.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The standard of safety level is the safety integrity level (SIL).
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] A safety PLC might be used to control access to a robot cell with trapped-key access, or to manage the shutdown response to an emergency stop button on a conveyor production line.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Such PLCs typically have a restricted regular instruction set augmented with safety-specific instructions designed to interface with emergency stop buttons, light screens, and other safety-related devices.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs are well adapted to a range of automation tasks.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically industrial processes in manufacturing where the cost of developing and maintaining the automation system is high relative to the total cost of the automation system, and where changes to the system would be expected during its operational life.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs contain input and output devices compatible with industrial devices and controls; little electrical design is required, and the design problem centers on expressing the desired sequence of operations.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] PLC applications are typically highly customized systems, so the cost of a packaged PLC is low compared to the cost of a specific custom-built controller design.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] On the other hand, in the case of mass-produced goods, customized control systems are economical.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] This is due to the lower cost of the components, which can be optimally chosen instead of a *generic* solution, and where the non-recurring engineering charges are spread over thousands or millions of units.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] These are for small machines and systems with low or medium volume.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] They can execute PLC languages such as ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] They are similar to traditional PLCs, but their small size allows developers to design them into custom printed circuit boards like a microcontroller, without computer programming knowledge, but with a language that is easy to use, modify and maintain.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Architecturally, they sit between the classic PLC or micro-PLC and microcontrollers.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Automotive applications are an example; millions of units are built each year, and very few end-users alter the programming of these controllers.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] However, some specialty vehicles, such as transit buses, economically use PLCs instead of custom-designed controllers, because the volumes are low and the development cost would be uneconomical.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Very complex process control, such as that used in the chemical industry, may require algorithms and performance beyond the capability of even high-performance PLCs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Very high-speed or precision controls may also require customized solutions; for example, aircraft flight controls.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Single-board computers using semi-customized or fully proprietary hardware may be chosen for very demanding control applications where the high development and maintenance cost can be supported.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] **Soft PLCs** running on desktop-type computers can interface with industrial I/O hardware while executing programs within a version of commercial operating systems adapted for process control needs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] The rising popularity of single-board computers has also had an influence on the development of PLCs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Traditional PLCs are generally closed platforms, but some newer PLCs (e.g., groov EPIC from Opto 22, ctrlX from Bosch Rexroth, PFC200 from Wago, PLCnext from Phoenix Contact, and Revolution Pi from Kunbus) provide the features of traditional PLCs on an open platform.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] In more recent years, small products called programmable logic relays (PLRs) or smart relays have become more common and accepted.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] These are similar to PLCs and are used in light industries where only a few points of I/O are needed, and low cost is desired.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] These small devices are typically made in a common physical size and shape by several manufacturers and branded by the makers of larger PLCs to fill their low-end product range.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Most of these have 8 to 12 discrete inputs, 4 to 8 discrete outputs, and up to 2 analog inputs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Most have an RS-232 or RS-485 port for connecting to a PC so that programmers can use user-friendly software for programming instead of the small LCD and push-button set for this purpose.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike regular PLCs that are usually modular and greatly expandable, the PLRs are usually not modular or expandable, but their cost can be significantly lower than that a PLC, and they still offer robust design and deterministic execution of the logic.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] A variant of PLCs, used in remote locations, is the remote terminal unit or RTU.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] An RTU is typically a low power, ruggedized PLC whose key function is to manage the communications links between the site and the central control system (typically SCADA) or in some modern systems, "The Cloud".
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike factory automation using wired communication protocols such as Ethernet, communications links to remote sites are often radio-based and are less reliable.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] To account for the reduced reliability, RTU will buffer messages or switch to alternate communications paths.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] When buffering messages, the RTU will timestamp each message so that a full history of site events can be reconstructed.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] RTUs, being PLCs, have a wide range of I/O and are fully programmable, typically with languages from the IEC 61131-3 standard that is common to many PLCs, RTUs and DCSs.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] In remote locations, it is common to use an RTU as a gateway for a PLC, where the PLC is performing all site control and the RTU is managing communications, time-stamping events and monitoring ancillary equipment.
[src:ot-security-ics/programmable-logic-controller] On sites with only a handful of I/O, the RTU may also be the site PLC and will perform both communications and control functions.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:ot-security-ics/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
